Soccer Dataset Analysis¶

Question posed : What are the attributes of a high ranking player ?¶

Data source and attributes¶

The data was downloaded from Kaggle. The tables present in the sqlite database are :

  1. Country
  2. League
  3. Match
  4. Player
  5. Player_Attributes
  6. Team
  7. Team_Attributes
The above list was retrieved by typing .tables in sqlite prompt.

Analysis Process¶

Splitting the players_data over multiple ranges based on ratings to understand the key differences between them.¶

In [7]:
# Query the players rated below 80 (overall_rating)
players_rated_below_80 = players_data.query('overall_rating <= 80')
# Sort the players in the ascending order of their rating
players_rated_below_80.sort_values(by=['overall_rating'])
# Take the mean of the ratings of all attributes for all players.
below80 = players_rated_below_80.describe().loc['mean']
# Remove the columns irrelevant to the comparision
below80.drop(['player_api_id', 'player_fifa_api_id', 'overall_rating', 'potential'], inplace=True)

Perform the same operations as above for the players rated above 80¶

In [8]:
players_rated_above_80 = players_data.query('overall_rating > 80')
players_rated_above_80.sort_values(by=['overall_rating'])
above80 = players_rated_above_80.describe().loc['mean']
above80.drop(['player_api_id', 'player_fifa_api_id', 'overall_rating', 'potential'], inplace=True)

Histograms and normal distribution of heights and weights of all players¶

In [12]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 10), frameon=False)
height = players_data['height']
weight = players_data['weight']
sns.distplot(height,kde=False, norm_hist=True, fit=stats.gamma, ax=ax[0])
sns.distplot(weight,kde=False, norm_hist=True, fit=stats.gamma, ax=ax[1])
height_std = round(players_data.describe().loc['std']['height'], 3)
weight_std = round(players_data.describe().loc['std']['weight'], 3)
fig.suptitle("Height and Weight distribution of all the players")
Out[12]:
Text(0.5, 0.98, 'Height and Weight distribution of all the players')

These histograms prove that the heights and weights of all the players are evenly distributed.
Standard deviation of height = 6.369 and weight = 14.99
Also, the mean difference in height of players ranked above 80 and below 80 = 0.39. The same statistic for weight = 3.6
Hence they're not deciding factors for judging a players ability and ranking.

The above graphs and statistics show that, there isn't much difference in the physical abilities of all the players. They are more or less the same, irrespective of their ranking. So, we can exclude these attributes from our comparison.¶

In [13]:
drop_columns = ['stamina', 'agility', 'strength', 'balance', 'jumping', 'sprint_speed', 'acceleration', 'height', 'weight']
above80.drop(drop_columns, inplace=True)
below80.drop(drop_columns, inplace=True)

In the above comparison, it is evident that, higher ranked players are able to control, dribble and kick the ball much better than a player ranked lower than 80. It should also be noted that, high ranked players have a better vision and faster reactions.¶

Conclusion¶

A player is ranked highly because of his abilities with the ball. His physical attributes ( body ) do not make a difference.
So, for a player to get good, he should focus more on the basics of ball play.

Limitations¶

The player_attributes table has been aggregated to give an average player statistic, as a result of which, we don't know how a players' ranking has changed ( increased or decreased ) over time.
Inclusion of the aforementioned statistic would add more weightage to our observations, enabling us to understand the rise journey of a player in a better way.
